Hi David,

Could you possibly elaborate on &quot;I can&#39;t comment on the history of 
assertNotEquals&quot; - I&#39;ve also been a little puzzled at this perceived gap 
in the JUnit 3.8.x API and would be interested to learn a bit more about 
the reason(s) behind it.

I agree that Assert#assertThrows is a little on the tricky side. 
Personally, I&#39;ve always gone for:

&lt;snip&gt;
try
{
   Integer.parseInt(&quot;not an int&quot;);
   fail(&quot;Should not be able to parse String as int.&quot;);
}
catch (Throwable expectedT)
{
   assertInstanceOf(expectedT, IllegalArgumentException.class);
}
&lt;/snip&gt;

I&#39;m willing to hear about other solutions, mind - provided that it 
doesn&#39;t involve upgrading to JUnit 4. Not an option right now. :(

